     <br/>
    </div>

<div class="page" id="page2">

      <b>Names of elements.</b> Different elements (types of atoms) are abbreviated with one or two letters. The first
      letter is always capitalized.
     <br/><br/>

      For example:

        <ul style="line-height:2;">
        <li>Hydrogen is abbreviated as "H".</li>
        <li>Helium is "He". (They couldn't use just "H", since it would be confused with hydrogen.)</li>
        <li>Carbon is "C".</li>
        <li>Chlorine is "Cl". (They couldn't use just "C", since it would be confused with carbon.)</li>
        <li>Oxygen is "O".</li>
      </ul>

     <br/>
    </div>

<div class="page" id="page3">

      <p>
        <b>Ions of elements</b>: Sometimes elements gain or lose one or more electrons. Because the atoms no longer
        have the same number of protons (+) and electrons (-), they have an electric charge. Atoms that have lost or
        gained electrons are called <b>ions</b>. 
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          One example of an ion is a hydrogen (H) atom that has lost an electron. It now has one proton (p+)
          but no electrons. So, the hydrogen ion has a positive charge. A hydrogen ion is written as H+. 
        </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
        <li>
          The "+" sign means that it has a "net" positive charge, or there are more (positively-charged) protons than
          (negatively-charged) electrons.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Another example of an ion is a Fluorine (F) atom that has gained an electron (e-). It now has one more
          electron than protons (p+), so it has a negative charge. A Fluorine ion (called Fluoride) is written as Fl-.  
        </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
        <li>
          The "-" sign means that it has a "net" <span style="color:#ff0000">negative</span> charge, or there are
          more (negatively-charged) electrons than (positively-charged) protons.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <br/>

      <form class="quiz_choice quiz">
        <b>Q0.6: The element Clorine (Cl) has 17 protons. Which of the following would be a Chlorine ion?</b>
        <input name="question" type="radio" value="incorrect"/>
        <div class="label">a) a Cl atom with 17 protons &amp; 17 electrons</div><br/>
        <input name="question" type="radio" value="correct"/>
        <div class="label">b) a Cl atom with 17 protons &amp; 18 electrons</div><br/>
        <input name="question" type="radio" value="incorrect"/>
        <div class="label">c) a Cl atom with 18 protons &amp; 17 electrons</div><br/>
        <input name="question" type="radio" value="incorrect"/>
        <div class="label">d) a Cl atom with 18 protons &amp; 18 electrons</div><br/>
        <button class="submit-btn" type="submit">Submit</button>
        <div class="feedback-correct feedback">
          Right! The element Chlorine always has 17 protons (that's how you know it's Chlorine). A Chlorine ion has a different number of
          electrons than protons. So, a Cl atom with 17 protons and 18 electrons is a Cl ion.
        </div>
        <div class="feedback-incorrect feedback">
          Well, the element Chlorine always has 17 protons (that's how you know it's Chlorine). A Chlorine ion has a different number of
          electrons than protons. So, a Cl atom with 17 protons and 18 electrons is a Cl ion.
        </div>
      </form>


     <br/>

